#Approach:

Approach:
Ye code stack use karke check karta hai ki kisi bracket pair ke andar actual operation hai ya nahi.

1. Expression ko left se right traverse karte hain.
2. Har character ko stack me push karte jaate hain, jab tak ')' na mil jaaye.
3. Jaise hi ')' milta hai, stack se pop karna start karte hain until '(' mile.
4. Is popped part ke andar agar koi operator (+, -, *, /) mil gaya,
   to brackets useful hain, yani redundant nahi hain.
5. Agar '(' tak pahunchne se pehle koi operator nahi mila,
   to iska matlab brackets ke andar sirf single element ya unnecessary expression tha,
   isliye brackets redundant hain → return true.
6. Agar poori string traverse ho gayi aur aisa koi case nahi mila, to return false.

Main idea:
Kisi bhi valid bracket pair ke andar agar operator hi nahi hai,
to wo bracket extra hai aur uski zarurat nahi hai.

Time Complexity: O(n)
Space Complexity: O(n)

#Code:

import java.util.Deque;
import java.util.ArrayDeque; 

public class Solution {
    public boolean hasRedundantBraces(String s) {
      // You can code here

      int n = s.length();
      Deque<Character> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();

      for(int i=0; i<n; i++){
        char ch = s.charAt(i);

        if(ch == ')'){
          char top = stack.pop();
          boolean flag = true;

          while(!stack.isEmpty() && top != '('){
            
            if(top == '+' || top == '-' || top == '*' || top == '/'){
              flag = false; //meaning bracket is not redundant
            }

            top = stack.pop();
          }
          if(flag == true){
            //meaning brackets are redundant
            return true;
          }
        }
        else{
          stack.push(ch);
        }
      }
      return false;

    }
}
